In his quest to discover and document new species of fish, he has also become a trailblazing exploratory diver and a pioneer of database technology. ", "whylisten": "

A pioneer of the dive world, Richard Pyle discovers new biodiversity on the cliffs of coral reefs. He was among the first to use rebreather technology to explore depths between 200 and 500 feet, an area often called the "Twilight Zone." During his dives, he has identified and documented hundreds of new species. Author of scientific, technical and popular articles, his expeditions have also been featured in the IMAX film Coral Reef Adventure, the BBC series Pacific Abyss and many more. In 2005, he received the NOGI Award, the most prestigious distinction of the diving world.

Currently, he is continuing his research at the Bernice P. Bishop Museum, outside Honolulu, Hawai'i, and is affiliated with the museum's comprehensive Hawaii Biological Survey. He also serves on the Board of Directors for the Association for Marine Exploration, of which he is a founding member. He continues to explore the sea and spearhead rebreather technology, and is a major contributor to the Encyclopedia of Life.

author: Richard_Pyle;
title: A dive into the reef's Twilight Zone

aws-transcripts.transcript: This is the first of two rather extraordinary photographs I'm gonna show you today was taken 18 years ago. I was 19 years old at the time. I just returned from one of the deepest dives that ever made at that time. A little over 200 feet. And I caught this little fish here. And it turns out that that particular one was the first live one of that ever taken alive. I'm not just a nick geologist. I'm a bona fide fish nerd into a fish inner. This is some pretty exciting stuff. And more exciting was the fact that the person who took this photo is a guy named Jack Randall, the greatest living, a geologist on Earth, the grand poobah of fish nerds, if you will. And so it was really exciting to me to have this moment in time. It really set the course of the rest of my life. But the really the most significant thing the most profound thing about this picture was taken two days before I was completely paralyzed from the neck down. It made a really stupid kind of mistake that most 19 year old males do when they think they're immortal and got a bad case of the bends and was paralyzed and had to be flown back for treatment. But I learned two really important things that day. The first thing I learned Well, I'm mortal. That's a really big one. And the second thing I learned was that I knew with profound certainty that this is exactly what I was gonna do for the rest of my life. I had to focus all my energies towards going to find new species of things down on deep coral reefs. Now, when you think of a coral reef, this is what most people think of all these big, hard, elaborate corals and lots of bright, colorful fishes and things. But this is really just the tip of the iceberg. If you look at the sort of diagram of a coral reef, we know a lot about that part up near the top and the reason we know so much about it. A scuba divers could very easily go down there and access it. There is a problem with scuba, though, and and it poses some limitations on how deep you can go. And it turns out that that depths about 200 feet. I'll get into why that is in just a minute. But the point that scuba divers generally stay less than 100 feet deep and very rarely go much below this, at least not with any kind of sanity. So to go deeper, most biologists turned to submersibles. Now, submersibles a great, wonderful things. But if you're gonna spend $30,000 a day to use one of these things and it's capable of going 2000 feet, you're sure not gonna go farting around up here in a couple of 100 feet, you're gonna go way, way, way down deep. So the bottom line is that almost all research using submersibles has taken place well below 500 feet. Now it's pretty obvious at this point. This is zone here in the middle, and that's the zone that really is centers around. My own personal pursuit of happiness is I want to find out what's in this zone. We know almost nothing about it. Scuba divers can't get their submarines go right on past it. It took me a year to learn how to walk again after I had my diving accident in Palau and During that year, I spent a lot of time learning about physics and physiology, of diving, figuring out how to overcome these limitations. So I'm just gonna show you a basic idea. We're all breathing air right now. Air is a mixture of oxygen and nitrogen, about 20% oxygen, about 80% nitrogen. It's in her lungs.
